        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3189006228" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1022488017155933911">This was a really interesting book, and I enjoyed the varied viewpoints, although I do wish the book could have been longer. I read the author&apos;s notes at the beginning and the end of the book and he explained how he really cut down/edited this story from hundreds of voices/stories to just 16. Personally, I think the story could have handled well with 25-30 voices, but that&apos;s my opinion.<br/><br/>People who live in the first world (in places that have been 1st world for a long time) often don&apos;t think about</span>
  <span id="freeText1022488017155933911" style="display:none">This was a really interesting book, and I enjoyed the varied viewpoints, although I do wish the book could have been longer. I read the author's notes at the beginning and the end of the book and he explained how he really cut down/edited this story from hundreds of voices/stories to just 16. Personally, I think the story could have handled well with 25-30 voices, but that's my opinion.<br /><br />People who live in the first world (in places that have been 1st world for a long time) often don't think about the impact that technology and increased standards of living has on developing countries, which is especially relevant in the 21st century with the internet, or the clash between "old-fashioned" people and people eager to embrace this technology. The author does a nice job of illustrating this in his various narratives, but I still wish there had been some more because I enjoyed it. :)<br /><br />4.25/5 stars</span>
